I've found a pretty serious showstopping bug; consider the following SSCCE:
```C#
using AtomicEngine;

public class Game : AppDelegate
{
    public static Input input;
    private Scene scene;
    
    public override void Start()
    {
        input = GetSubsystem<Input>();

        scene = new Scene();
        scene.CreateComponent<Octree>();
        
        var camNode = scene.CreateChild("cameraNode");
        camNode.Position = new Vector3(0,0,-5);
        GetSubsystem<Renderer>().SetViewport(0, new Viewport(scene, camNode.CreateComponent<Camera>()));

        var physicsWorld2D = scene.CreateComponent<PhysicsWorld2D>();
        physicsWorld2D.Gravity = Vector2.UnitY*-0.1f;
        
        var node = scene.CreateChild("node");
        node.CreateComponent<RigidBody2D>().BodyType = BodyType2D.BT_DYNAMIC;
        
        SubscribeToEvent<UpdateEvent>(MyUpdate);

        physicsWorld2D.DrawCenterOfMass = true;
        var dbgr = scene.CreateComponent<DebugRenderer>();
        SubscribeToEvent<PostRenderUpdateEvent>(e => physicsWorld2D.DrawDebugGeometry(dbgr, false));
    }

    private void MyUpdate(UpdateEvent eventdata)
    {
        if (input.GetMouseButtonDown(Constants.MOUSEB_LEFT))
        {
            scene.CreateChild();
        }
    }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Application.Run<Game>(args);
    }
}
```
When you click the mouse a new node will be created each frame, however, note how the object 'freezes' on screen, i.e.: while you're holding the mouse, gravity won't affect the object. I've tried doing other stuff when the mouse is pressed to see if the same would happen, but it didn't.
PS: I found this issue in a 2D shooter I was trying to make: each bullet fired would pause the game for that frame.

# TO-DO
- [ ] Clamp Magnitude
- [ ] Use a better approach for Vector Operations
- [ ] Expose/port the entire Math API to Scripting
- [ ] Easy Eulerian angles rotation API
- [ ] 2D Direction Setter

# Discussion and Details

## Clamp Magnitude
A way to clamp the magnitude of a vector is generally useful, especially when dealing with non normalized input, here's my quick implementation in C# (extension):
```C#
public static Vector2 ClampMagnitude(this Vector2 v, float maxMagnitude)
    {
        if (v.Length <= maxMagnitude)
            return v;
        return Vector2.Normalize(v) * maxMagnitude;
    }
```

## Vector Operations
It's somewhat confusing the fact that something like `MyVector3.Normalize()` is valid but won't work, and apparently the correct usage is `Vector3.Normalize(MyVector3)`... imho we should provide instance methods for these unary operations

## Expose/port the entire Math API to Scripting
We don't have the API to raycast AABBs and some types are lacking too

## Easy Eulerian angles rotation API
Provide a way to rotate and set rotation that takes Eulerian angles, ~~and also a way to easily build a Quaternion from them~~

## 2D Direction Setter
basically:
```C#
public static void SetDirection2D(this Node n, Vector2 direction)
{
    n.Rotation2D = (float)(Math.Atan2(direction.X, -direction.Y) / Math.PI) * 180;
}
```

Consider the following code based on an empty C# project:
```c#
Scene s = AtomicNET.GetSubsystem<Player>().LoadScene("Scenes/Scene.scene");
DebugRenderer a = s.CreateComponent<DebugRenderer>();
DebugRenderer b = s.GetComponent<DebugRenderer>();
Debug.WriteLine($"ret obj: {a.ID}");
Debug.WriteLine($"get obj: {b.ID}");
```
It's obvious that a and b should be the same object since there are no other DebugRenderers, but they aren't. CreateComponent is creating and returning a different component than the one that's being actually added to the scene, so two DebugRenderers are created there. This could represent a memory leak since the object returned is indeed valid and has a proper unmanaged object bound to it.

UIMultiList
These are 2 classes that enable the UISelectList to have multiple columns.  There is API to set the column type, column width, data for the column and fixing the column height, if necessary. Once set into the UISelectList, it operates the same way, to get which row is selected.

There are a couple of column types that can be used
  TEXT = which is a TextField, with left justified text, the column data is the text that will be displayed.
  TEXTC = a TextField, with center justified text
  TEXTR = a TextField with right justified text
  IMAGE = an ImageWidget, the column data is the resource name (or pathname) to the file to display
  COLOR = a ColorWidget, the column data is the hex color string, like "#228800", to display.
  ICON = a SkinImage, the column data is the skin name for the icon to display.
  
If the column height is left as 0, the content will determine the height of the row. If you need it to be a fixed size, the column height field can be used.
The columm widths must be programmed, and are needed to keep alignment for the widget, the content will not exceed the programmed value.

Example Javascript code
```
    var mis = new Atomic.UIMultiItemSource();  // new itemsource

    var columnHeight = 0;   // 0 = let content determine column height
    var  = "item1";   // RefId string returned when list entry is selected
	var aumi1 = new Atomic.UIMultiItem( columnRefId, "ICON", "LogoAtomic", 32, columnHeight );
	aumi1.addColumn ( "TEXT", "a new kind of list...", 210 );
	aumi1.addColumn ( "TEXTC", "RW",  20 );
	aumi1.addColumn ( "COLOR", "#33FF33", 20 );
	aumi1.addColumn ( "TEXT", "moar", 66 );
	aumi1.addColumn ( "TEXT", "moar text is fine, in multiple columns.", 266 );
    mis.addItem( aumi1 );
    
    mylist.setSource(mis);

```
